Spoken Language is known as speech. Speech is a sequence of sounds that conveys a meaning.
A \textit{syllable} is a basic unit in a speech.
For example, in English, the phonetic of the word ``music'' contains two syllables.\footnote{Chinese phonetic is also called pinyin.} They are \textipa{[mju:]} and \textipa{[zIk]}.
In Mandarin, the phonetic of the word ``音'' contains 1 syllable. It is [y\={\i}n].
\end{CJK*}
There is a mark on top of the i in [y\={\i}n]. It is a tone symbol. It tells us how to pronounce this syllable with correct tone.

The languages can be classified as \textit{tonal} or \textit{non-tonal languages}. For both kinds of language, there are tone variations. Even in non-tonal languages, people do not speak in monotone!
However, if someone speaks a sentence in monotone in English, others can still understand. The meaning of the sentence will not be ambiguous.
In tonal languages, the tone of a word is important for distinguishing the word from another.
	
